SOURCE.title: PupaSNP_v30
SOURCE.description:
http://pupasnp.bioinfo.cipf.es/
We have developed a web tool, PupaSNP, for for high-throughput search of SNPs with potential phenotypic effect at transcriptional level.
PupaSNP inputs lists of genes (or generates them from chromosomal coordinates) and retrieves SNPs that could affect to conserved regions that the cellular machinery uses for the correct processing of genes (intron/exon boundaries or exonic splicing enhancers), predicted transcription factor binding sites, or causes changes in amino acids in proteins. The program uses the mapping of SNPs in the genome provided by Ensembl.
Aditionally, user-defined SNPs (not yet mapped in the genome) can be easily provided to the program. Also, additional functional information from gene ontology, OMIM and homologies in other model organisms is provided.

SOURCE.title: Pfam Other Features
SOURCE.description:
Pfam other features contains active site residues, disulphide bonds, regions of low complexity, coiled coiled regions, and signal peptides.
Active site residues There are two types of active site residues: experimental and predicted. The experimental active site residues are taken from UniProt, and the predicted active site residues are computationally predicted by Pfam using an automated rule based methodology.
Disulphide bonds This data is taken from UniProt
Low complexity This data is computationally generated using the seg program
Coiled coiled regions This data is computationally generated using the ncoils program
Signal peptides This data is computationally generated using the SignalP software

SOURCE.title: BioViz PlantGDB proxy
SOURCE.description: This is simply a proxy for another DAS site. All requests are forwarded to the second site (at http://www.plantgdb.org/cgi-bin/das) and the output is parsed and then returned, with a couple of alterations. First, the XML is modified to allow parsing, and second, the LINK href attribute is changed so that LINK tags point to the NCBI Web site. PlantGDB uses Genbank 'gi' numbers as ids for alignments, and so rather than point to the PlantGDB site, the new XML provides links to Genbank records at NCBI. This is mainly a convenience for visualization of data in the Integrated Genome Browser.

SOURCE.title: PPDB_das
SOURCE.description: PPDB (http://ppdb.tc.cornell.edu) is a specialized proteome database dedicated to plant plastids. It is a joint project between Klaas J. van Wijk Lab and the Computational Biology Service Unit of Cornell University. The main objective is to provide a centralized, curated, data deposit for predicted and experimentally determined plastid proteins in Arabidopsis thaliana and maize (Zea mays), their annotated functions, as well as their experimental and predicted molecular and biophysical properties. All gene models in the Arabidopsis nuclear and organellar genomes as annotated by TAIR, as well as all maize EST assemblies (ZmGI) and maize genome sequence assemblies (AZM) as annotated by TIGR. The das server of PPDB provide the peptide sequences that are identified in each protein sequences.
